passages.text: S.F. Holding reported mixed 2Q print with in- line revenue growth of \(+11\%\) yoy, while pre- exceptional net profit (excluding a Rmb1bn investment gain) came in below- expectations at Rmb2.6bn, \(- 13\%\) vs. GSe, with gross margin at \(13.1\%\) (vs. \(14.5\%\) in 2Q24) as a result of flexible pricing strategy amid S.F's proactive focus on market share in 2Q25 amid competition. We lay out the key investor focus points post- print and our thoughts on:

1) Market share gain in time-definite express on accelerated order volume growth: SF delivered in-line \(7\%\) revenue growth for time-definite express in 1H25, remained at above-GDP level growth, with an acceleration of \(19\%\) yoy overall parcel volume growth mainly driven by flexible pricing strategy, where the company expanded market share to \(8.2\%\) in 1H25 (vs. \(7.4\%\) in 2H24). GS view: We expect time definite express revenue to grow \(7\%\) yoy in 2025E (unchanged), with accelerated volume growth yet decline in ASP. Alongside healthy growth of economy/freight/supply chain & international, we expect group revenue growth of \(10\% /9\%\) in 3Q/2025E (prior: \(8\% /9\%\) ).

2) Softer near-term margin outlook, yet set for margin improvement in 2026, where SF delivered lower-than-expected gross margin (13.1% vs. GSe of \(14.6\%\) ) and EBIT margin miss (5.1% vs. GSe of \(6.0\%\) ) in 2Q25, on the back of flexible pricing strategy and partly offset increasing operating efficiency. As the company plans to further invest in improving service quality and continue to adopt flexible pricing strategy to expand market share, we expect gross margin to face short-term pressure. That being said, the company remains confident in executing margin improvement in 2026 on the back of enlarged volume and revenue base. GS views: We expect gross margin of \(13.4\% /13.3\%\) in 3Q25/FY25E (prior: \(14.2\% /14.1\%\) ), and a net margin of \(3.8\% /3.7\%\) (prior: \(4.1\% /3.8\%\) ).

3) Supply chain and international growth under tariff uncertainty: SF grew supply chain and international revenue by \(10\%\) yoy in 1H25 (-2% vs. GSe). Despite the growth acceleration compared to 2H24 under tariff uncertainty, we believe the business remains resilient under the secular theme of Chinese companies' overseas expansion, with the company's enhanced cross-border multimodal capabilities (107

all cargo aircraft, 79 customs clearance service ports, etc.). GS views: We expect SF's supply chain and international revenue to grow at \(10\%\) in 2025E (from \(+6\%\) prior), by leveraging its Asia's largest fleet, comprehensive network spanning China and SEA, and cost advantages compared to other Big 3 international integrated logistics peers operating in the regions.

4) Favorable shareholder return policy supported by strong free cash flow: SF announced that it will distribute Rmb2.3bn as FY25 interim dividends, with dividend payout ratio at \(40\%\) , supported by strong cash flow generation on the back of decreasing capex. In 1H25, SF's capex (excluding equity investment) declined by \(24\%\) to Rmb4.2bn (2.9% of total revenue vs. 4.1% a year ago), as major investment projects substantially completed (e.g. Ezhou Air Cargo Hub completed in 2023). core net profit estimates by \(4\% - 5\%\) on better-than- expected international freight forwarding profit. We remain Neutral on Kerry Logistics with an unchanged methodology for our SOTP- based 12- m TP of HK\\$9.0 (prior: HK\\$8.3) on risks around forwarding rates/geopolitical uncertainties.

Key risks: 1) margin improvement supported by accelerated integration between SF and Kerry; 2) stronger- than- expected global trade and business activity; 3) better- than- expected cash flow improvement from the divestment of loss- making business; 4) moderating competition in the China contract logistics and/or ASEAN express delivery market.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
